A '''bioanalytical equivalent''' (BEQ) is a unit of measure in the field of [[bioassays]]. It is used for example in the bioassay [[CALUX]] for testing [[dioxins and dioxin-like compounds]].<ref>{{cite journal|last=Baston|first=David S.|author2=Michael S. Denison|title=Considerations for potency equivalent calculations in the Ah receptor-based CALUX bioassay: Normalization of superinduction results for improved sample potency estimation|journal=Talanta|date=15 February 2011|volume=83|issue=5|pages=1415–1421|url=http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0039914010009124|accessdate=27 March 2014|doi=10.1016/j.talanta.2010.11.035|pmc=3036574}}</ref>
