{{About|coded aperture masks|other uses|Mura (disambiguation){{!}}Mura}}

A '''modified uniformly redundant array'''  ('''MURA''')  is a type of mask used in [[coded aperture|coded aperture imaging]].

==Mathematical Construction of MURAs==

MURAs can be generated in any length ''L'' that is prime and of the form
:<math> L =  4m +1, \ \  m = 1,2,3,...,</math>
the first six such values being <math>L = 5,13,17,29,37</math>. The binary sequence of a linear MURA is given by <math> A = {A_i}_{i=0}^{L-1}</math>, where 
:<math> 
A_i = \begin{cases}
  0  & \mbox{if } i = 0, \\
  1  & \mbox{if } i \mbox{ is a quadratic residue modulo } L, i \neq 0,\\
 0   & \mbox{otherwise}
\end{cases}
</math>
These linear MURA arrays can also be arranged to form hexagonal MURA arrays. One may note that if <math> L = 4m  + 3 </math> and <math>A_0 = 1 </math>, a uniformly redundant array(URA) is a generated.

As with any mask in coded aperture imaging, an inverse sequence must also be constructed. In the MURA case, this inverse ''G'' can be constructed easily given the original coding pattern ''A'': 
:<math> 
G_i = \begin{cases}
  +1   & \mbox{if } i = 0, \\
  +1  & \mbox{if } A_i = 1, i \neq 0,\\
 -1  & \mbox{if } A_i = 0, i \neq 0, 
\end{cases}
</math>
Rectangular MURA arrays are constructed in a slightly different manner, letting <math> A = \{A_{ij}\}_ {i,j  =0}^{p-1}  </math>, where
:<math> 
A_{ij} = \begin{cases} 
0 & \mbox{if } i = 0, \\
1 & \mbox{if } j = 0, i \neq 0, \\
1 & \mbox{if } C_i C_j = +1, \\
0  & \mbox{otherwise,} 
\end{cases} 
</math>
and 
:<math> 
C_i  = \begin{cases} 
+1 & \mbox{if } i \mbox{ is a quadratic residue modulo }p, \\
- 1 & \mbox{otherwise,}
\end{cases} 
</math>
[[File:MURA mask, size 101.jpg|thumb|right|A rectangular MURA mask of size 101]]
The corresponding decoding function ''G'' is constructed as follows:
:<math> 
G_{ij} = \begin{cases} 
+1 & \mbox{if } i + j = 0; \\
+1 & \mbox{if } A_{ij} = 1,  \ (i+j \neq 0); \\
-1 & \mbox{if } A_{ij} = 0, \ (i+j \neq 0),;
\end{cases} 
</math>

[[Category:Arrays]]
[[Category:Radiation]]

{{Infobox mineral|name=Owensite|image=|alt=|caption=|category=|formula=(Ba, Pb)<sub>6</sub>(Cu, Fe, Ni)<sub>25</sub>S<sub>27</sub>|strunz=|dana=|system=Isometric|class=Hexoctahedral|symmetry=cubic|unit cell=|color= pale brownish grey|colour=|habit=|twinning=|cleavage=|fracture=|tenacity=|mohs=|luster=Metallic|streak=|diaphaneity=|gravity=|density=|polish=|opticalprop=|refractive=|birefringence=|pleochroism=|2V=|dispersion=|extinction=|length fast/slow=|fluorescence=|absorption=|melt=|fusibility=|diagnostic=|solubility=|impurities=|alteration=|other=|prop1=|prop1text=|references=<ref>Szymanski, Jan T. "The crystal structure of owensite,(Ba, Pb) 6 (Cu, Fe, Ni) 25 S 27, a new member of the djerfisherite group." The Canadian Mineralogist 33.3 (1995): 671-677.</ref><ref name=mindat>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mindat.org/min-7211.html|title=Owensite: Owensite mineral information and data.|website=www.mindat.org|access-date=2017-12-30}}</ref>}}

'''Owensite''' is a mineral discovered in the Wellgreen Cu-Ni-Pt-Pd deposit, Yukon, with the formula (Ba, Pb)<sub>6</sub>(Cu, Fe, Ni)<sub>25</sub>S<sub>27</sub>. The mineral is related to [[djerfisherite]], but lacks the Cl and monovalent metals found in the latter.

